 surface-specific test commands | 1. Identify detected surface; 2. Load surface standards; 3. Separate style/process from security/correctness |\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/SKILL.retired.md:- **Agent-Delegated Tasks** — specialized profile matches (`.codex/agents/*n`), session management (resume, fork), multi-strategy planning.\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/SKILL.retired.md:**Profile setup**: Defined in `.codex/confign` under `[profiles.<name>]`. Each profile can override `model`, `model_reasoning_effort`, `sandbox_mode`, and `approval_policy`. The `.codex/agents/*n` files provide agent definitions for the interactive multi-agent TUI feature.\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/codex_tools.md:| **Agent system** | `.claude/agents/` | `.codex/agents/*n` | Both support specialized agents |\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/agent_delegation.md:Codex CLI tasks are routed using the `-p` / `--profile` flag with a profile name. Profiles are defined in `confign` under `[profiles.<name>]` sections. For git diff reviews, use the built-in `codex exec review` subcommand.\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/agent_delegation.md:Profiles must be defined in `confign`. Example configuration matching the agent catalog below:\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/agent_delegation.md:# .codex/confign\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/agent_delegation.md:**Note:** The `.codex/agents/*n` files define agent personas for the interactive multi-agent TUI feature. They are NOT loaded by the `-p` profile flag. To use agent-specific behavior in `codex exec`, define corresponding `[profiles.<name>]` sections in confign and include context in the prompt.\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/agent_delegation.md:| Profile not found   | Error: profile not defined          | Verify profile name matches `[profiles.<name>]` in confign |\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/README.md:Route to a specialized Codex agent through the repo-local agent surface. `.codex/confign` declares `[agents.<name>]` entries whose `config_file` values point at `.codex/agents/<name>n`; the `.codex/agents/` directory holds the Codex-side agent files. The roster is larger than the old six-profile set.\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/cli_reference.md:- Configuring agents via `.codex/agents/*n`\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/cli_reference.md:# .codex/agents/my-agentn — reasoning-heavy agent\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/cli_reference.md:# .codex/agents/my-codegen-agentn — code-focused agent\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/cli_reference.md:Each agent is a `n` file in `.codex/agents/`. Fields:\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/cli_reference.md:# .codex/agents/examplen\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/cli_reference.md:**Note:** The `.codex/agents/*n` files define agent personas for the interactive multi-agent TUI feature (requires `multi_agent` feature flag). They are NOT loaded by the `-p` profile flag. To use agent-specific settings in `codex exec`, define corresponding `[profiles.<name>]` sections in confign.\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/manual_testing_playbook/04--agent-routing/research-profile.md:| CX-026 | @research profile (web-grounded investigation) | Verify -p research --search returns a citation-backed comparative analysis with a recommendation | `As a cross-AI orchestrator delegating an evidence-backed investigation, dispatch codex exec -p research --search --model gpt-5.5 -c model_reasoning_effort=\"high\" -c service_tier=\"fast\" --sandbox read-only \"Compare current Bun and Deno major releases across runtime performance, package ecosystem, and operational stability. Cite at least one HTTPS source URL per candidate. End with a recommendation plus rationale.\" Verify the dispatch routes via -p research, cites at least 2 HTTPS URLs, names both candidates with explicit pros and cons, and ends with a recommendation. Return a verdict naming the cited URLs, the trade-off dimensions covered, and the recommendation.` | 1. `codex exec -p research --search --model gpt-5.5 -c model_reasoning_effort=\"high\" -c service_tier=\"fast\" --sandbox read-only \"Compare current Bun and Deno major releases across runtime performance, package ecosystem, and operational stability. Cite at least one HTTPS source URL per candidate. End with a recommendation plus rationale.\" </dev/null > /tmp/cli-codex-cx026.txt 2>&1` -> 2. `bash: echo \"Exit: $?\"` -> 3. `bash: grep -ciE '(bun\\|deno)' /tmp/cli-codex-cx026.txt` -> 4. `bash: grep -ciE '(performance\\|ecosystem\\|stability)' /tmp/cli-codex-cx026.txt` -> 5. `bash: grep -oE 'https://[a-zA-Z0-9./_-]+' /tmp/cli-codex-cx026.txt \\| sort -u \\| wc -l \\| tr -d ' '` -> 6. `bash: grep -ciE '(recommend\\|recommendation)' /tmp/cli-codex-cx026.txt` | Step 1: dispatch captured; Step 2: exit 0; Step 3: count of candidate mentions >= 4 (each candidate >= 2 times); Step 4: count of dimension mentions >= 3; Step 5: distinct HTTPS URL count >= 2; Step 6: recommendation count >= 1 | `/tmp/cli-codex-cx026.txt`, terminal exit code, grep counts, URL count | PASS if exit 0 AND >= 2 candidates AND >= 3 dimensions AND >= 2 HTTPS URLs AND recommendation present AND `-p research` plus `--search` in dispatch; FAIL if any check misses | (1) Define `[profiles.research]` in confign if missing per agent_delegation.md §3 (sandbox_mode = \"workspace-write\" but the profile here uses --sandbox read-only as the override); (2) re-run after `codex login` if rate limits or auth errors surface; (3) if URL count is 0, --search may not have engaged, capture stderr and check for `--search` recognition |\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/manual_testing_playbook/04--agent-routing/research-profile.md:| `.codex/confign` (or `~/.codex/confign`) | `[profiles.research]` section |\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/manual_testing_playbook/04--agent-routing/review-profile.md:- Expected execution process: Operator confirms `.codex/confign` has a `[profiles.review]` section -> snapshots `git status --porcelain` -> dispatches with `-p review` -> captures stdout -> verifies categorized findings -> re-snapshots and confirms no diffs.\n.claude/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/manual_testing_playbook/04--agent-routing/review-profile.md:1. Confirm `.codex/confign` has a `[profiles.review]` section (or note that the profile must be created per `agent_delegation.md` §2 Profile Setup).\n\n=== Cluster 6: cli-opencode/SKILL.md lines 285-300 ===\nOpenCode defines `general`, `plan`, and `orchestrate` as primary agents. **Caveat — never pass `--agent general`:** the current opencode treats `general` as a subagent and rejects it at the top level, and the default agent (used when no `--agent` is given) already covers that case. Pin `--agent plan|orchestrate` only when the task needs that profile AND `opencode run --help` on the installed version confirms top-level acceptance; otherwise state the role in the prompt body.\n\n#### Subagents — dispatched as Task subagents from a primary\n\nThese live at `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md` with `mode: subagent` and are NOT directly invokable via `opencode run --agent`. Three dispatch surfaces are legal under the single-hop NDP contract:\n\n1. **Generic subagents** (`context`, `review`, `write`, `debug`) — dispatched by a primary (`orchestrate`) using the Task tool. To exercise via the opencode CLI, route through `--agent orchestrate` and let it dispatch the relevant subagent.\n2. **`ai-council`** — dispatched either via its own `/deep:ai-council` command or via `orchestrate`'s registry-backed Task-dispatch. Direct `--agent ai-council` is rejected at the top level (`mode: subagent`); route through `/deep:ai-council` or `--agent orchestrate` with an ai-council-shaped prompt.\n3. **Command-owned loop executors** (`deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-improvement`, `prompt-improver`) — LOOP-OWNED by their parent commands (`/deep:research`, `/deep:review`, `/deep:agent-improvement`, `/prompt`), which own iteration state, convergence detection, and continuity. Never dispatch these directly via raw `--agent <slug>` from the CLI. `orchestrate` is an authorized **caller/coordinator only** for these agents (e.g. its registry-backed `/deep:review` Priority row) — it may perform exactly one bounded hand-off dispatch to the resolved leaf, but MUST NOT re-implement the loop (no iterating, no convergence checks, no continuity tracking); that remains the parent command's job.\n\nGeneric subagents (`context`, `review`, `write`, `debug`) and `ai-council` route through `orchestrate` for full Task-tool dispatch; loop executors (`deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-improvement`, `prompt-improver`) are loop-owned by their parent commands, with `orchestrate` limited to a single bounded hand-off when it recognizes one of these as the target.\n\nSee [agent_delegation.md](./references/agent_delegation.md) for the complete agent roster and dispatch patterns.\n\n### Unique OpenCode Strengths\n\n","exit":0,"truncated":false},"title":"echo \"=== REPO-WIDE .opencode/agents/*.toml (beyond stated scope) ===\"\nrg -rn -- \"\\.opencode/agents/\\*\\.toml|agents/\\{name\\}\\.toml\" .opencode/ .claude/ AGENTS.md 2>/dev/null | rg -v \"node_modules\" | head -20 || echo \"(zero repo-wide)\"\necho \"\"\necho \"=== Broader: any '*.toml' mirror/agent reference in skills docs (non-changelog) ===\"\nrg -rn -- \"\\.toml\" .opencode/skills/ .claude/skills/ 2>/dev/null | rg -v \"node_modules|changelog/|target_manifest\" | rg -i \"agent|mirror\" | head -20 || echo \"(zero non-changelog .toml agent/mirror refs)\"\necho \"\"\necho \"=== Cluster 6: cli-opencode/SKILL.md lines 285-300 ===\"\nsed -n '285,300p' .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md 2>/dev/null","time":{"start":1782925280479,"end":1782925280481}},"id":"prt_f1ea0c364001SxqQOc3SzUX0c4","sessionID":"ses_0e161eb7effeWxawnzJ6Yp6rgG","messageID":"msg_f1ea0296f001rDgupGHxK6WnUS"}}
